"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation is fundamentally challenged by non-Lambertian surfaces, where specular and scattering reflections violate the epipolar plane image (EPI) linearity assumption. Existing methods heavily rely on high-resolution angular spectra or uniform EPI constraints, leading to severe performance degradation under low angular resolution and complex reflectance. To address this, we propose a unified dual-mask physical model that decouples illumination, depth, and material properties through a novel three-layer angular signal decomposition. Specifically, we model the angular signal as a superposition of a direct current component, linear disparity, and a material residual. Instead of relying on fragile frequency features, we extract robust geometric features, such as angular gradients, to train a random forest classifier for precise Lambertian and non-Lambertian pixel segregation. These physical priors guide a GeometricDualMask architecture, which adaptively routes pixels to specialized EPI and geometric processing branches via a dual-mask mechanism, optimized with domain-balanced sampling. Extensive evaluations across three datasets demonstrate that our method achieves an overall mean absolute error (MAE) of 0.133 and a mixed/urban scene MAE of 0.081, significantly outperforming state-of-the-art baselines. Furthermore, the material classifier attains an 89.6% accuracy and a 0.962 area under the curve. By explicitly modeling the physical boundaries of EPI assumptions, this work provides a theoretically grounded, signal-processing framework for robust depth estimation in complex reflective environments.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field imaging, depth estimation, non-Lambertian reflectance, angular signal decomposition, epipolar plane image, dual-mask routing."